05549nam a22006855i 9780226825748DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2022039125  a9780226825748  a(DE-B1597)649731  a(OCoLC)1348334016  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aB802b.S735 2023 4aB802b.S735 2023 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a190223/eng/202210191 aStatman, Alexander, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Global Enlightenment :bWestern Progress and Chinese Science /cAlexander Statman. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b27 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Life of Ideas00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tOne. The Death of Voltaire’s Confucius -- tTwo. The Ex- Jesuit Mission in China -- tThree. The Origins of Esotericism -- tFour. The Yin- Yang Theory of Animal Magnetism -- tFive. The Invention of Eastern Wisdom -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA revisionist history of the idea of progress reveals an unknown story about European engagement with Chinese science. The Enlightenment gave rise not only to new ideas of progress but consequential debates about them. Did distant times and places have anything to teach the here and now? Voltaire could believe that they did; Hegel was convinced that they did not. Early philosophes praised Chinese philosophy as an enduring model of reason. Later philosophes rejected it as stuck in the past. Seeking to vindicate ancient knowledge, a group of French statesmen and savants began a conversation with the last great scholar of the Jesuit mission to China. Together, they drew from Chinese learning to challenge the emerging concept of Western advancement. A Global Enlightenment traces this overlooked exchange between China and the West to make compelling claims about the history of progress, notions of European exceptionalism, and European engagement with Chinese science. To tell this story, Alexander Statman focuses on a group of thinkers he terms “orphans of the Enlightenment,” intellectuals who embraced many of their contemporaries’ ideals but valued ancient wisdom. They studied astronomical records, gas balloons, electrical machines, yin-yang cosmology, animal magnetism, and Daoist medicine. And their inquiries helped establish a new approach to the global history of science. Rich with new archival research and fascinating anecdotes, A Global Enlightenment deconstructs two common assumptions about the early to late modern period. Though historians have held that the idea of a mysterious and inscrutable East was inherent in Enlightenment progress theory, Statman argues that it was the orphans of the Enlightenment who put it there: by identifying China as a source of ancient wisdom, they turned it into a foil for scientific development. But while historical consensus supposes that non-Western ideas were banished from European thought over the course of the Enlightenment, Statman finds that Europeans became more interested in Chinese science—as a precursor, then as an antithesis, and finally as an alternative to modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivilization, WesternxChinese influences. 0aEast and West. 0aEnlightenment. 0aProgressxPhilosophyxHistory. 0aScience and civilization. 0aSciencexHistory. 0aSciencezChina. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aglobal, Enlightenment, idea of progress, history of science, French history, Chinese history, early modern Europe, Joseph-Marie Amiot, Orientalism, Needham Question.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE